# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ackee
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ackee/academic-press] Academic Press publishes books and reference materials in fields including communications engineering, economics, environmental science, finance, food science, geophysics, life sciences, mathematics, neuroscience, psychology, and the physical sciences.
[src:ackee/ackee-and-saltfish] The ackee fruit (*Blighia sapida*) is the national fruit of Jamaica.
[src:ackee/ackee-and-saltfish] It was brought to the Caribbean from Ghana before 1725 as 'Ackee' or 'Aki', another name for the Akan people, Akyem.
[src:ackee/ackee-and-saltfish] The fruit's scientific name honours Captain William Bligh who took the fruit from Jamaica to the Royal Botanic Gardens in Kew, England in 1793 and introduced it to science.
[src:ackee/ackee-and-saltfish] Because parts of the fruit are toxic, such as the arils prior to the opening of the husk at the ripening stage, there are shipping restrictions when being imported to countries such as the United States.
[src:ackee/ackee-and-saltfish] Salted codfish, on the other hand, was introduced to Jamaica for enslaved people as a long-lasting and inexpensive protein source.
[src:ackee/ackee-and-saltfish] In west Africa, ackee is mainly used as medicine or an ingredient for soap and is not consumed as food.
[src:ackee/ackee-and-saltfish] In other parts of west africa like among the northern Cote d’Ivoire in the Katiola, Sinématiali, and Khorogho regions, ackee is consumed as food, typically as a dried paste, and in the Toussiana and Peni divisions in Burkina Faso.
[src:ackee/ackee-and-saltfish] To prepare the dish, salt cod is sautéed with boiled ackee, onions, Scotch bonnet peppers, tomatoes, then seasoned with spices like pepper and paprika.
[src:ackee/ackee-and-saltfish] It can be garnished with bacon and tomatoes, and is usually served as breakfast alongside breadfruit, hard dough bread, dumplings, or boiled green bananas.
[src:ackee/ackee-and-saltfish] Ackee and Saltfish can also be eaten with rice and peas or plain white rice.
[src:ackee/ackee-and-saltfish] When seasonings (onion, scallion, thyme, garlic) and saltfish are combined with plain rice it is often called "seasoned rice", which can be a one-pot meal including ackee.
[src:ackee/ackee-and-saltfish] Ackee and Saltfish is widely regarded as the national dish of Jamaica.
[src:ackee/ackee-and-saltfish] According to *The Guardian*, Jamaican sprinter Usain Bolt often has Ackee and Saltfish for breakfast.
[src:ackee/ackee-and-saltfish] Harry Belafonte's 1956 hit song "Jamaica Farewell" declares, "Ackee rice, Saltfish are nice".
[src:ackee/ackee] The **ackee** (***Blighia sapida***), also known as **ackee apple**, is a fruit of the Sapindaceae (soapberry) family, as are the lychee and the longan.
[src:ackee/ackee] The scientific name honours Captain William Bligh who took the fruit from Jamaica to the Royal Botanic Gardens in Kew, England, in 1793.
[src:ackee/ackee] The English common name is derived from the West African Akan-language name *akye fufo*.
[src:ackee/ackee] Although having a long-held reputation as being poisonous with potential fatalities, the fruit arils are renowned as delicious when ripe, prepared properly, and cooked and are a feature of various Caribbean cuisines.
[src:ackee/ackee] Ackee is the national fruit of Jamaica and is considered a delicacy.
[src:ackee/ackee] Ackee is an evergreen tree that grows about 10 metres tall, with a short trunk and a dense crown.
[src:ackee/ackee] The leaves are paripinnately, compound 15–30 centimetres (6–12 inches) long, with 6–10 elliptical to oblong leathery leaflets.
[src:ackee/ackee] The inflorescences are fragrant, up to 20 cm long, with unisexual flowers that bloom during warm months.
[src:ackee/ackee] Each flower has five greenish-white petals, which are fragrant.
[src:ackee/ackee] The fruit is pear-shaped and has three lobes (two to four lobes are common).
[src:ackee/ackee] When it ripens it turns from green to a bright red to yellow-orange and splits open to reveal three large, shiny black seeds, each partly surrounded by soft, creamy or spongy, white to yellow flesh — the aril having a nut-like flavour and texture of scrambled eggs.
[src:ackee/ackee] The tree can produce fruit throughout the year, although January–March and October–November are typically periods of fruit production.
[src:ackee/ackee] There are up to as many as forty-eight cultivars of ackee, which are grouped into either "butter" or "cheese" types.
[src:ackee/ackee] The cheese type is pale yellow in colour and is more robust and finds use in the canning industry.
[src:ackee/ackee] The butter type is deeper yellow in color, and is more delicate and better suited for certain cuisine.
[src:ackee/ackee] Imported to Jamaica from West Africa before 1773, the use of ackee in Jamaican cuisine is prominent.
[src:ackee/ackee] Ackee is the national fruit of Jamaica, while ackee and saltfish is the official national dish of Jamaica.
[src:ackee/ackee] The ackee is allowed to open fully before picking in order to eliminate toxicity.
[src:ackee/ackee] When it has "yawned" or "smiled", the seeds are discarded and the fresh, firm arils are parboiled in salted water or milk, and may be fried in butter to create a dish.
[src:ackee/ackee] In Caribbean cooking, they may be cooked with codfish and vegetables, or may be added to stew, curry, soup or rice with seasonings.
[src:ackee/ackee] Ackee contains a moderate amount of carbohydrates, protein, and fat, providing 51–58% of the dry weight of the arils as composed of fatty acids – linoleic, palmitic, and stearic acids.
[src:ackee/ackee] The raw fruit is a rich source of vitamin C.
[src:ackee/ackee] The ackee is prominently featured in the Jamaican mento-style folk song "Linstead Market".
[src:ackee/ackee] In the song, a market seller laments, "Carry mi ackee go a Linstead market.
[src:ackee/ackee] The Beat's 1982 album *Special Beat Service* includes the song "Ackee 1-2-3".
[src:ackee/ackee] The unripened aril and the inedible portions of the fruit contain hypoglycin toxins including hypoglycin A and hypoglycin B, known as "soapberry toxins".
[src:ackee/ackee] Hypoglycin A is found in both the seeds and the arils, while hypoglycin B is found only in the seeds.
[src:ackee/ackee] Minimal quantities of the toxin are found in the ripe arils.
[src:ackee/ackee] In the unripe fruit, depending on the season and exposure to the sun, the concentrations may be up to 10 to 100 times greater.
[src:ackee/ackee] These two molecules are converted in the body to methylenecyclopropylacetic acid (MCPA), and are toxic with potential lethality.
[src:ackee/ackee] MCPA and hypoglycin A inhibit several enzymes involved in the breakdown of acyl CoA compounds, often binding irreversibly to coenzyme A, carnitine and carnitine acyltransferase I and II, reducing their bioavailability and consequently inhibiting beta oxidation of fatty acids.
[src:ackee/ackee] Glucose stores are consequently depleted leading to hypoglycemia, and to a condition called Jamaican vomiting sickness.
[src:ackee/ackee] These effects occur only when the unripe aril (or an inedible part of the fruit) is consumed.
[src:ackee/ackee] Though ackee is used widely in traditional dishes, research on its potential hypoglycin toxicity has been sparse and preliminary, requiring evaluation in well-designed clinical research to better understand its pharmacology, food uses, and methods for detoxification.
[src:ackee/ackee] In 2011, it was found that as the fruit ripens, the seeds act as a sink whereby the hypoglycin A in the arils convert to hypoglycin B in the seeds.
[src:ackee/ackee] In other words, the seeds help in detoxifying the arils, bringing the concentration of hypoglycin A to a level that is generally safe for consumption.
[src:ackee/ackee] Ackee canned in brine is a commodity item and is used for export by Jamaica, Haiti and Belize.
[src:ackee/ackee] If propagated by seed, trees will begin to bear fruit in 3–4 years.
[src:ackee/ackee] The fruit has various uses in West Africa and in rural areas of the Caribbean Islands, including use of its "soap" properties as a laundering agent or fish poison.
[src:ackee/ackee] The fragrant flowers may be used as decoration or cologne, and the durable heartwood used for construction, pilings, oars, paddles and casks.
[src:ackee/ackee] In African traditional medicine, the ripe arils, leaves or bark were used to treat minor ailments.
[src:ackee/ackee] The seeds were formerly used as standardized weights for weighing gold dust, leading to the currency issued by Great Britain in the former colony of Gold Coast to be named the "Gold Coast ackey".
[src:ackee/acyl-coa] Fats are broken down by conversion to acyl-CoA.
[src:ackee/acyl-coa] This conversion is one response to high energy demands such as exercise.
[src:ackee/acyl-coa] The oxidative degradation of fatty acids is a two-step process, catalyzed by acyl-CoA synthetase.
[src:ackee/acyl-coa] Fatty acids are converted to their acyl phosphate, the precursor to acyl-CoA.
[src:ackee/acyl-coa] Three types of acyl-CoA synthases are employed, depending on the chain length of the fatty acid.
[src:ackee/acyl-coa] For example, the substrates for medium chain acyl-CoA synthase are 4-11 carbon fatty acids.
[src:ackee/acyl-coa] The enzyme acyl-CoA thioesterase takes of the acyl-CoA to form a free fatty acid and coenzyme A.
[src:ackee/acyl-coa] The second step of fatty acid degradation is beta oxidation.
[src:ackee/acyl-coa] After formation in the cytosol, acyl-CoA is transported into the mitochondria, the locus of beta oxidation.
[src:ackee/acyl-coa] Transport of acyl-CoA into the mitochondria requires carnitine palmitoyltransferase 1 (CPT1), which converts acyl-CoA into acylcarnitine, which gets transported into the mitochondrial matrix.
[src:ackee/acyl-coa] Once in the matrix, acylcarnitine is converted back to acyl-CoA by CPT2.
[src:ackee/acyl-coa] Beta oxidation may begin now that Acyl-CoA is in the mitochondria.
[src:ackee/acyl-coa] Beta oxidation of acyl-CoA occurs in four steps.
[src:ackee/acyl-coa] Enoyl-CoA hydrase catalyzes the addition of water across the newly formed double bond to make an alcohol.
[src:ackee/acyl-coa] 3-hydroxyacyl-CoA dehydrogenase oxidizes the alcohol group to a ketone.
[src:ackee/acyl-coa] Thiolase cleaves between the alpha carbon and ketone to release one molecule of Acetyl-CoA and the Acyl-CoA which is now 2 carbons shorter.
[src:ackee/acyl-coa] This four step process repeats until acyl-CoA has removed all carbons from the chain, leaving only Acetyl-CoA.
[src:ackee/acyl-coa] During one cycle of beta oxidation, Acyl-CoA creates one molecule of Acetyl-CoA, FADH2, and NADH.
[src:ackee/acyl-coa] Acetyl-CoA is then used in the citric acid cycle while FADH2 and NADH are sent to the electron transport chain.
[src:ackee/acyl-coa] These intermediates all end up providing energy for the body as they are ultimately converted to ATP.
[src:ackee/acyl-coa] Beta oxidation, as well as alpha-oxidation, also occurs in the peroxisome.
[src:ackee/acyl-coa] The peroxisome handles beta oxidation of fatty acids that have more than 20 carbons in their chain because the peroxisome contains very-long-chain Acyl-CoA synthetases.
[src:ackee/acyl-coa] These enzymes are better equipped to oxidize Acyl-CoA with long chains that the mitochondria cannot handle.
[src:ackee/acyl-coa] Beta oxidation removes 2 carbons at a time, so in the oxidation of an 18 carbon fatty acid such as Stearic Acid 8 cycles will need to occur to completely break down Acyl-CoA.
[src:ackee/acyl-coa] This will produce 9 Acetyl-CoA that have 2 carbons each, 8 FADH2, and 8 NADH.
[src:ackee/acyl-coa] Heart muscle primarily metabolizes fat for energy and Acyl-CoA metabolism has been identified as a critical molecule in early stage heart muscle pump failure.
[src:ackee/acyl-coa] Cellular acyl-CoA content correlates with insulin resistance, suggesting that it can mediate lipotoxicity in non-adipose tissues.
[src:ackee/acyl-coa] Acyl-CoA: diacylglycerol acyltransferase (DGAT) plays an important role in energy metabolism on account of key enzyme in triglyceride biosynthesis.
[src:ackee/acyl-coa] The synthetic role of DGAT in adipose tissue such as the liver and the intestine, sites where endogenous levels of its activity and triglyceride synthesis are high and comparatively clear.
[src:ackee/acyl-coa] Also, any changes in the activity levels might cause changes in systemic insulin sensitivity and energy homeostasis.
[src:ackee/acyl-coa] A rare disease called multiple acyl-CoA dehydrogenase deficiency (MADD) is a fatty acid metabolism disorder.
[src:ackee/acyl-coa] Acyl-CoA is important because this enzyme helps make Acyl-CoA from free fatty acids, and this activates the fatty acid to be metabolized.
[src:ackee/acyl-coa] This compromised fatty acid oxidation leads to many different symptoms, including severe symptoms such as cardiomyopathy and liver disease and mild symptoms such as episodic metabolic decomposition, muscle weakness and respiratory failure.
[src:ackee/acyl-coa] MADD is a genetic disorder, caused by a mutation in the ETFA, ETFB, and ETFDH genes.
[src:ackee/acyl-coa] MADD is known as an "autosomal recessive disorder" because for one to get this disorder, one must receive this recessive gene from both parents.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] The **Agricultural Research Service** (**ARS**) is the principal in-house research agency of the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA).
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] ARS is one of four agencies in USDA's Research, Education and Economics mission area.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] ARS is charged with extending the nation's scientific knowledge and solving agricultural problems through its four national program areas: nutrition, food safety and quality; animal production and protection; natural resources and sustainable agricultural systems; and crop production and protection.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] ARS research focuses on solving problems affecting Americans every day.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] The ARS Headquarters is located in the Jamie L.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] Whitten Building on Independence Avenue in Washington, D.C., and the headquarters staff is located at the George Washington Carver Center (GWCC) in Beltsville, Maryland.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] For 2023, the budget grew to $1.9 billion.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] ARS conducts scientific research for the American public.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] ARS research complements the work of state colleges and universities, agricultural experiment stations, other federal and state agencies, and the private sector.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] ARS research may often focus on regional issues that have national implications, and where there is a clear federal role.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] ARS also provides information on its research results to USDA action and regulatory agencies and to several other federal regulatory agencies, including the Food and Drug Administration and the United States Environmental Protection Agency.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] ARS disseminates much of its research results through scientific journals, technical publications, *Agricultural Research* magazine, and other forums.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] Information is also distributed through ARS's National Agricultural Library (NAL).
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] ARS has more than 150 librarians and other information specialists who work at two NAL locations—the Abraham Lincoln Building in Beltsville, Maryland; and the DC Reference Center in Washington, D.C.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] NAL provides reference and information services, document delivery, interlibrary loan and interlibrary borrowing services to a variety of audiences.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] Prior to the inception of ARS, agricultural research was first conducted under the umbrella of the Agricultural Department in the U.S.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] It was created to collect statistics, distribute seeds and compile and distribute pertinent information.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] In 1862 the USDA was created and agricultural research was moved to its department.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] That same year, the department issued its first research bulletin on the sugar content of grape varietals and their suitability for wine.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] Six years later the USDA would begin its first research on animal diseases, specifically hog cholera, which was causing devastating losses at the time.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] In the early 1900s the USDA began analyzing food composition and the first studies of nutrition and the effects of cooking and processing foods were conducted.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] Finally, in 1953 the Agricultural Research Service was created to be the USDA's primary scientific research agency.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] ARS supports more than 2,000 scientists and post docs working on approximately 690 research projects within 15 National Programs at more than 90 research locations.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] The ARS is divided into 5 geographic areas: Midwest Area, Northeast Area, Pacific West Area, Plains Area, and Southeast Area.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] The research centers focus on innovation in agricultural practices, pest control, health, and nutrition among other things.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] Work at these facilities has given life to numerous products, processes, and technologies.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] Wallace Beltsville Agricultural Research Center (BARC) in Beltsville, Maryland, is the world's largest agricultural research complex.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] Other D.C. area locations include the United States National Agricultural Library and the United States National Arboretum.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] ARS also has six major human nutrition research centers that focus on solving a wide spectrum of human nutrition questions by providing authoritative, peer-reviewed, science-based evidence.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] The centers are located in Arkansas, Maryland, Texas, North Dakota, Massachusetts (the Human Nutrition Research Center on Aging), and California.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] ARS scientists at these centers study the role of food and dietary components in human health from conception to advanced age.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] The ARS also offers the Culture Collection, which is the largest public collection of microorganisms in the world, containing approximately 93,000 strains of bacteria and fungi.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] The ARS Culture Collection is housed at the National Center for Agricultural Utilization Research (NCAUR).
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] There is also a collection of entomopathogenic fungi, called ARSEF, at the Robert W.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] Holley Center for Agriculture and Health in Ithaca, New York.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] Horticultural Research Laboratory in Fort Pierce, Florida, and the U.S.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] National Poultry Research Center in Athens, Georgia.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] Other notable ARS facilities include Northern Great Basin Experimental Range in Oregon, and formerly the Plum Island Animal Disease Center off Long Island.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] Several ARS research units focus on pests, diseases, and management practices of horticultural crops.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] The Cereal Disease Laboratory is located on the campus of the University of Minnesota in Saint Paul.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] It primarily hosts research into rusts and *Fusaria* of cereals.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] The San Joaquin Valley Agricultural Sciences Center in Parlier, California conducts research on specialty crops including grapes, citrus, almonds, alfalfa, peaches, pomegranates, and many others.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] Several research locations throughout the US also house germplasm collections of plant species important for agricultural and industrial uses as part of the **National Genetic Resources Program**.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] From the very beginning the Department of Agriculture and in turn the Agricultural Research Service has been focused on improving not only the farming industry but also the quality of food and the health of Americans.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] In 1985, technology to produce lactose-free milk, yogurt, and ice cream was developed through the Agricultural Research Service.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] The grape breeding program, currently located in Parlier, CA which began in 1923, developed seedless grapes and continues to release new grapevine varieties with improved traits.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] The ARS Citrus and Subtropical Products Laboratory in Winter Haven, Florida, actively works to improve the taste of orange juice concentrate.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] The Agricultural Research Service had a *Toxoplasma gondii* (*T. gondii*) research program, which experimented on cats infected with the parasite, from 1982 until 2018.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] The prevalence of *T. gondii* parasite has been reduced by 50% in the U.S.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] As of September 2018, which the ARS claims is a result of their research.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] The USDA has since discontinued the use of cats in their research amid acute accusations of animal abuse, and a lack of meaningful contribution to the field in recent years (only three of thirteen papers published about *T. gondii* by the ARS were published after the year 2000).
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] More recently, the ARS has focused research on genetics and plant and animal DNA.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] Their research has developed pest-resistant corn, faster growing plants and fish, and a focus on plant and animal genome research and mapping.
[src:ackee/agricultural-research-service] Outside of scientific research, the ARS has worked to release databases on food components in order to assist consumers with making informed decisions about food choices.
[src:ackee/akan-language] Three dialects of Twi-Fante were developed as literary standards with distinct orthographies: Asante Twi, Akuapem Twi, and Fante.
[src:ackee/akan-language] Despite being mutually intelligible, they were inaccessible in written form to speakers of the other standards until the Akan Orthography Committee (AOC)'s development of a common Twi-Fante orthography in 1978, based mainly on Akuapem dialect.
[src:ackee/akan-language] As the first Akan variety to be used for Bible translation, Akuapem Twi had become the prestige dialect.
[src:ackee/akan-language] With the Atlantic slave trade, Akan languages, principally Twi/Fante, were introduced to the Caribbean and South America, notably in Suriname and Jamaica, where they heavily influenced the language of the Ndyuka and the Jamaican Maroons, also known as the Coromantee.
[src:ackee/akan-language] The cultures of the descendants of escaped slaves in the interior of Suriname and the Maroons in Jamaica still retain Akan influences, including the Akan naming practice of naming children after the day of the week on which they are born, e.g.
[src:ackee/akan-language] Akwasi/Kwasi for a boy or Akosua for a girl born on a Sunday, etc.
[src:ackee/akan-language] In Jamaica and Suriname, the *Ananse* spider stories are still well-known.
[src:ackee/akan-language] Originally, the language was known by local names rather than a single unifying term.
[src:ackee/akan-language] Inland Akan groups referred to it as 'Twi' (/tʃwiː, twiː, tʃiː/; Akan: [tɕᶣi]), while coastal Akan groups referred to it as 'Fante'.
[src:ackee/akan-language] After independence, the national language commission adopted 'Akan', a name that had been used for all the languages spoken by the Akan people, which includes the Bia languages in addition to Twi-Fante, as a unitary name for Twi-Fante specifically.
[src:ackee/akan-language] The broader scope was renamed Central Tano to avoid ambiguity.
[src:ackee/akan-language] However, many sources still refer to all the languages spoken by the Akan people as 'Akan'.
[src:ackee/akan-language] The largest Akan migration was to Ghana in successive waves between the 11th and 18th centuries.
[src:ackee/akan-language] Smaller numbers migrated to the eastern part of Côte d'Ivoire and parts of Togo.
[src:ackee/akan-language] Within Ghana, the Akan expanded from the north to occupy the southern forest and coastal areas during the 13th century.
[src:ackee/akan-language] The Akans have a strong oral history tradition of their past and are also known in for symbolic artifacts of wood, metal and terracotta.
[src:ackee/akan-language] Their cultural ideas are expressed in stories and proverbs as well as in designs such as symbols used in carvings and on clothes.
[src:ackee/akan-language] The rich Akan culture and history in Ghana are areas of research for many disciplines, such as folklore, literary studies, linguistics, anthropology, and history.
[src:ackee/akan-language] Twi-Fante is a dialect continuum that is closely related to the Bia languages and the other Akan languages that are spoken by the Akan people.
[src:ackee/akan-language] Brong and Wasa have limited mutual intelligibility with each other, and so are separate languages by that standard.
[src:ackee/akan-language] Neighboring Brong and Asante are mutually intelligible, though geographically more distant Brong and Fante are less so.
[src:ackee/akan-language] The Twi-Fante dialects contain extensive palatalization, vowel harmony, and tone terracing.
[src:ackee/akan-language] Before front vowels, all Asante consonants are palatalized (or labio-palatalized), and the stops are to some extent affricated.
[src:ackee/akan-language] The allophones of /n/ are quite complex.
[src:ackee/akan-language] In the table below, palatalized allophones which involve more than minor phonetic palatalization are specified, in the context of the vowel /i/.
[src:ackee/akan-language] These sounds do occur before other vowels, such as /a/, though in most cases not commonly.
[src:ackee/akan-language] In Asante, /ɡu/ followed by a vowel is pronounced /ɡʷ/, but in Akuapem it remains /ɡu/.
[src:ackee/akan-language] A word final /k/ can be heard as a glottal stop [ʔ].
[src:ackee/akan-language] There is also a nasalization of /h/ and of /j w/ as [h̃] and [j̃ w̃], when occurring before nasal vowels.
[src:ackee/akan-language] The transcriptions in the tables below are in the order /phonemic/, [phonetic].
[src:ackee/akan-language] Note that orthographic ⟨dw⟩ is ambiguous; in textbooks, ⟨dw⟩ = /ɡ/ may be distinguished from /dw/ with a diacritic: *d̩w*.
[src:ackee/akan-language] Likewise, velar ⟨nw⟩ (ŋw) may be transcribed *n̩w*.
[src:ackee/akan-language] All fourteen were distinguished in the Gold Coast alphabet of the colonial era.
[src:ackee/akan-language] A tongue-root distinction in orthographic *a* is only found in some subdialects of Fante, but not in the literary form; in Asante and Akuapem there are harmonic allophones of /a/, but neither is ATR.
[src:ackee/akan-language] The two vowels written *e* (/e/ and /i̙/) and *o* (/o/ and /u̙/) are often not distinguished in pronunciation.
[src:ackee/akan-language] Twi-Fante vowels engage in a form of vowel harmony with the root of the tongue.
[src:ackee/akan-language] After the +RTR non-high vowels /e̙ a̙ o̙/, −RTR mid vowels /e o/ become +RTR high vowels /i̙ u̙/.
[src:ackee/akan-language] This is not reflected in the orthography, for both sets of vowels are spelled ⟨e o⟩, and in many dialects this rule does not apply, for these vowels have merged.
[src:ackee/akan-language] Initial syllable may only be *high* or *low*.
[src:ackee/akan-language] The phonetic pitch of the three tones depends on their environment, often being lowered after other tones, producing a steady decline known as tone terracing.
[src:ackee/akan-language] /H/ tones have the same pitch as a preceding /H/ or /M/ tone within the same tonic phrase, whereas /M/ tones have a lower pitch.
[src:ackee/akan-language] That is, the sequences /HH/ and /MH/ have a level pitch, whereas the sequences /HM/ and /MM/ have a falling pitch. /H/ is lowered (downstepped) after a /L/.
[src:ackee/akan-language] /L/ is the default tone, which emerges in situations such as reduplicated prefixes.
[src:ackee/akan-language] It is always at bottom of the speaker's pitch range, except in the sequence /HLH/, in which case it is raised in pitch but the final /H/ is still lowered.
[src:ackee/akan-language] Thus /HMH/ and /HLH/ are pronounced with distinct but very similar pitches.
[src:ackee/akan-language] After the first "prominent" syllable of a clause, usually the first high tone, there is a downstep.
[src:ackee/akan-language] Twi-Fante historically employed a noun class system similar to that of Bantu languages.
[src:ackee/akan-language] Although this system is now largely defunct, remnants of it persist in modern Twi-Fante plural formation, particularly through prefixes and suffixes.
[src:ackee/akan-language] The current pluralisation system blends fossilised class prefixes with newer morphological strategies, especially for human nouns.
[src:ackee/akan-language] Notably, human nouns have preserved more elements of the old system than non-human nouns and can employ multiple plural-marking strategies simultaneously.
[src:ackee/akan-language] Modern Twi-Fante employs several strategies for plural formation, representing a transition from its historical purely prefixal system to a mixed system using both prefixes and suffixes.
[src:ackee/akan-language] These strategies vary based on semantic categories, with human nouns showing particularly complex patterns.
[src:ackee/akan-language] Many Twi-Fante nouns form their plurals through the addition or replacement of nasal prefixes (*m-*, *n-*), reflecting remnants of the old noun class system.
[src:ackee/akan-language] In this process, the original class prefix (typically *a-*) is replaced by a homorganic nasal prefix that assimilates to the initial consonant of the root word.
[src:ackee/akan-language] For example, initial *ab-* becomes *mm-* and *ad-* becomes *nn-* in plural forms.
[src:ackee/akan-language] A relatively newer morphological development involves using plural suffixes, primarily for human and agentive nouns.
[src:ackee/akan-language] This development is particularly significant as it shows how Twi-Fante is evolving from its historical prefix-based system.
[src:ackee/akan-language] Human nouns demonstrate the most complex plural marking, often combining both old prefixal and new suffixal strategies — a pattern that highlights their special status in the language's grammatical system.
[src:ackee/akan-language] This suffix is used primarily for kinship and social role terms.
[src:ackee/akan-language] This suffix is used with profession- or agent-based nouns.
[src:ackee/akan-language] In some cases, both a prefix and a suffix are used for pluralisation, especially with human nouns (e.g., *onua* → *enuanom*).
[src:ackee/akan-language] This double marking represents a unique development in the Twi-Fante plural system, where human nouns have not only preserved elements of the old class system but have also incorporated new morphological strategies, resulting in a more complex marking pattern than non-human nouns.
[src:ackee/akan-language] Certain Twi-Fante nouns remain unchanged in the plural, representing another way the historical noun class system has been simplified.
[src:ackee/akan-language] While human nouns have developed complex plural marking strategies, these invariant nouns — including mass nouns and inherently plural items — have moved in the opposite direction by eliminating plural marking entirely.
[src:ackee/akan-language] Twi-Fante originally featured a more extensive system of noun classes marked by singular/plural prefixes.
[src:ackee/akan-language] Over time, this class system has undergone morphological decay.
[src:ackee/akan-language] Modern Twi-Fante lacks productive class agreement between nouns and adjectives or verbs, and many prefixes have become fossilised elements perceived as part of the noun stem.
[src:ackee/akan-language] The letters C, J, Q, V, X and Z are also used, but only in loanwords.
[src:ackee/akan-language] The Akan languages have a rich literature in proverbs, folktales, and traditional drama, as well as a new literature in dramas, short stories, and novels.
[src:ackee/akan-language] This literature began to be documented in written form in the late 1800s.
[src:ackee/akan-language] Later, Joseph Hanson Kwabena Nketia collected a number of proverbs and folktales, including *Funeral Dirges of the Akan People* (1969), *Folk Songs of Ghana* (1963), and *Akan Poetry* (1958).
[src:ackee/akan-language] Some of the important authors in the language are A.
[src:ackee/akan-language] The Bureau of Ghana Languages has been unable to continue printing novels in the language, and the following are out of print: *Obreguo, Okrabiri, Afrakoma, Obeede, Fia Tsatsala,*and *Ku Di Fo Nanawu*.
[src:ackee/akan-language] In 1978 the AOC established a unified "Akan" orthography for Twi-Fante, which is used as the medium of instruction in primary school.
[src:ackee/akan-language] Literacy in Twi-Fante is counted toward general literacy, from at least the lower primary level (primary 1–3).
[src:ackee/akan-language] Twi-Fante is studied at several major universities in the United States, including Ohio University, Ohio State University, University of Wisconsin-Madison, Harvard University, Boston University, Indiana University, University of Michigan, and The University of Florida.
[src:ackee/akan-language] Twi-Fante has been a regular African language of study in the annual Summer Cooperative African Languages Institute (SCALI) program.
[src:ackee/akan-language] The Twi-Fante language is studied in these universities as a bachelor or masters program.
[src:ackee/akan-language] The Akan people use a common naming system of giving the first name to a child, based on the day of the week that the child was born.
[src:ackee/akan-language] Most of the nations in Ghana have a similar custom, which extends to neighboring countries.
[src:ackee/aril] An **aril** (/ˈærɪl/), also called **arillus** (plural *arilli*), is a specialized outgrowth from a seed that partly or completely covers the seed.
[src:ackee/aril] An **arillode**, or **false aril**, is sometimes distinguished: whereas an aril grows from the attachment point of the seed to the ovary (from the funiculus or *hilum*), an arillode forms from a different point on the seed coat.
[src:ackee/aril] The term "aril" is sometimes applied to any fleshy appendage of the seed in flowering plants, such as the mace of the nutmeg seed.
[src:ackee/aril] Arils and arillodes are often edible enticements that encourage animals to transport the seed, thereby assisting in seed dispersal.
[src:ackee/aril] **Pseudarils** are aril-like structures commonly found on the pyrenes of Burseraceae species that develop from the mesocarp of the ovary.
[src:ackee/aril] The fleshy, edible pericarp splits neatly in two halves, then falling away or being eaten to reveal a brightly coloured pseudaril around the black seed.
[src:ackee/aril] The aril may create a fruit-like structure, called (among other names) a *false fruit*.
[src:ackee/aril] False fruit are found in numerous Angiosperm taxa.
[src:ackee/aril] The edible false fruit of the longan, lychee and ackee fruits are highly developed arils surrounding the seed rather than a pericarp layer.
[src:ackee/aril] Such arils are also found in a few species of gymnosperms, notably the yews and related conifers such as the lleuque and the kahikatea.
[src:ackee/aril] Instead of the woody cone typical of most gymnosperms, the reproductive structure of the yew consists of a single seed that becomes surrounded by a fleshy, cup-like covering.
[src:ackee/aril] This covering is derived from a highly modified cone scale.
[src:ackee/aril] In European yew plants (*Taxus baccata*), the aril starts out as a small, green band at the base of the seed, then turns brown to red as it enlarges and surrounds the seed, eventually becoming fleshy and scarlet in color at maturity.
[src:ackee/aril] The aril is attractive to fruit-eating birds and is non-toxic.
[src:ackee/aril] All other parts of the yew are toxic, including the seed housed inside the aril.
[src:ackee/aril] If the seed is crushed, breaks or splits in the stomach of a human, bird or another animal, it will result in poisoning.
[src:ackee/aril] Birds digest the fleshy aril as a food source, and pass the seeds out in their droppings, promoting dispersal of the seeds.
[src:ackee/aril] The kahikatea tree, *Dacrycarpus dacrydioides*, is native to New Zealand.
[src:ackee/aril] In pre-European times the aril of the kahikatea was a food source for Māori.
[src:ackee/aril] The washed arils were called *koroi* and were eaten raw.
[src:ackee/bambara-language] Bambara is a variety of a group of closely related languages called Manding, whose native speakers trace their cultural history to the medieval Mali Empire.
[src:ackee/bambara-language] Manding is part of the larger Mandé family of languages.
[src:ackee/bambara-language] Bambara is spoken throughout Mali as a lingua franca.
[src:ackee/bambara-language] The language is most widely spoken in the areas east, south, and north of Bamako, where native speakers and/or those that identify as members of the Bambara ethnic group are most densely populated.
[src:ackee/bambara-language] These regions are also usually considered to be the historical geographical origin of Bambara people, particularly Ségou, after diverging from other Manding groups.
[src:ackee/bambara-language] The main dialect is Standard Bamara, which has significant influence from Maninkakan.
[src:ackee/bambara-language] The language has two (mid/standard and high) tones; e.g.
[src:ackee/bambara-language] Since 1967, Bambara has mostly been written in the Latin script, using some additional phonetic characters from the Africa Alphabet.
[src:ackee/bambara-language] The vowels are *a, e, ɛ* (formerly *è*), *i, o, ɔ* (formerly *ò*), *u*; accents can be used to indicate tonality.
[src:ackee/bambara-language] The former digraph *ny* is now written *ɲ* when it designates a palatal nasal; the *ny* spelling is kept for the combination of a nasal vowel with a subsequent oral palatal glide.
[src:ackee/bambara-language] Following the 1966 Bamako spelling conventions, a velar nasal "ŋ" is written as "ŋ", although in early publications it was often transcribed as *ng* or *nk*.
[src:ackee/bambara-language] The N'Ko (N'Ko: ߒߞߏ) alphabet is a script devised by Solomana Kante in 1949 as a writing system for the Manding languages of West Africa; N'Ko means 'I say' in all Manding languages.
[src:ackee/bambara-language] Kante created N'Ko in response to what he felt were beliefs that Africans were a "cultureless people" since prior to this time there had been no indigenous African writing system for his language.
[src:ackee/bambara-language] N'ko first gained a strong user base around the Maninka-speaking area of Kante's hometown of Kankan, Guinea and disseminated from there into other Manding-speaking parts of West Africa.
[src:ackee/bambara-language] N'ko, and the Arabic script, also known as the Ajami script, are still in use for Bambara, although only the Latin-based orthography is officially recognized in Mali.
[src:ackee/bambara-language] Additionally, a script known as Masaba or Ma-sa-ba was developed for the language beginning in 1930 by Woyo Couloubayi (c.
[src:ackee/bambara-language] Named for the first characters in Couloubayi's preferred collation order, Masaba is a syllabary which uses diacritics to indicate vowel qualities such as tone, length, and nasalization.
[src:ackee/bambara-language] As of 1978, Masaba was in limited use in several communities in Nioro Cercle for accounting, personal correspondence, and the recording of Muslim prayers; the script's current status and prevalence is unknown.
[src:ackee/bambara-language] It uses seven vowels a, e, ɛ, i, o, ɔ and u, each of which can be nasalized, pharyngealized and murmured, giving a total number of 21 vowels (the letters approximate their IPA equivalents).
[src:ackee/bambara-language] Writing with the Latin alphabet began during the French colonization, and the first orthography was introduced in 1967.
[src:ackee/bambara-language] Literacy is limited, especially in rural areas.
[src:ackee/bambara-language] Although written literature is only slowly evolving (due to the predominance of French as the "language of the educated"), there exists a wealth of oral literature, which is often tales of kings and heroes.
[src:ackee/bambara-language] This oral literature is mainly passed on by the griots (*Jeliw* in Bambara) who are a mixture of storytellers, praise singers, and human history books who have studied the trade of singing and reciting for many years.
[src:ackee/bambara-language] Many of their songs are very old and are said to date back to the old empire of Mali.
[src:ackee/bambara-language] The basic sentence structure is subject–object–verb (SOV).
[src:ackee/bambara-language] Take the phrase, *n t'a lon* (I don't know [it]).
[src:ackee/bambara-language] *n* is the subject (I), *a* is the object (it), and *[ta] lon* is the verb ([to] know).
[src:ackee/bambara-language] The *t'* is from the negative present tense marker *té*, *bé* being the affirmative present tense marker (*n b'a don* would mean "I know it").
[src:ackee/bambara-language] Like many SOV languages, Bambara uses postpositions rather than prepositions - their role being similar to English prepositions but placed after the noun.
[src:ackee/bambara-language] The typical argument structure of the language consists of a subject, followed by an aspectival auxiliary, followed by the direct object, and finally a transitive verb.
[src:ackee/bambara-language] Gender for a noun can be specified by adding a suffix, *-cɛ* or *-kɛ* for male and *-muso* for female.
[src:ackee/bambara-language] The plural is formed by attaching a vocalic suffix *-u*, most often with a low tone (in the orthography, *-w*) to nouns or adjectives.
[src:ackee/bambara-language] In urban areas, many Bamanankan conjunctions have been replaced in everyday use by French borrowings that often mark code-switches.
[src:ackee/bambara-language] However, one could also say: *I ka kulosi ye nɛrɛmukuman ye*, also meaning "your skirt is yellow." The original Bamanankan word for yellow comes from "*nɛrɛmuku*," being flour (*muku*) made from néré (locust bean), a seed from a long seed pod.
[src:ackee/bambara-language] Nɛrɛmuku is often used in sauces in Southern Mali.
[src:ackee/bambara-language] Most French loan words are suffixed with the sound 'i'; this is particularly common when using French words which have a meaning not traditionally found in Mali.
[src:ackee/bambara-language] For example, the Bamanankan word for snow is *niegei*, based on the French word for snow *neige*.
[src:ackee/bambara-language] As there has never been snow in Mali, there was no unique word in Bamanankan to describe it.
[src:ackee/bambara-language] Is Dou Mara still living in the United States?
[src:ackee/bambara-language] Malian artists such as Oumou Sangaré, Sidiki Diabaté, Fatoumata Diawara, Rokia Traoré, Ali Farka Touré, Habib Koité and the married duo Amadou & Mariam often sing in Bambara.
[src:ackee/bambara-language] Lyrics in Bambara occur on *Stevie Wonder's Journey Through "The Secret Life of Plants".* In 2010, Spanish rock group Dover released its 7th studio album *I Ka Kené* with the majority of lyrics in Bambara, Spanish, English and French.
[src:ackee/bambara-language] American rapper Nas also released a track titled "Patience" in 2010, which featured Damian Marley and extensively sampled the Amadou & Mariam song "Sabali", as *sabali* is a Bambara word meaning patience.
[src:ackee/bambara-language] Bambara was until 2023 one of several languages designated by Mali as a national language.
[src:ackee/bambara-language] In 2023, after a new constitution was approved by a majority of voters, Bambara became co-official, together with 12 other languages spoken in the country.
[src:ackee/bambara-language] French was removed as the official language and was kept only as a working language.
